Conflict of obligations from different principles
Group A - Applied ethics at large
[
{
  "id": 1,
  "premise": "Bob asks if a dress suits him. You can tell a comforting lie or tell the harsh truth, but not both. You should promote others’ wellbeing. You should not lie.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to tell the truth.",
  "label": "Conflict between different principles (Honesty vs. Beneficence)",
  "explanation": "There is a prima facie obligation to tell a lie to promote Bob’s psychological wellbeing, and there is a prima facie obligation to tell the truth because you should not lie. In this case, telling the truth takes priority because Bob trusts you to be honest."
}

{
  "id": 2,
  "premise": "You just met Bob. You do not like how Bob is dressed. Bob asks if you like his outfit. You should be polite. You should not lie.",
  "hypothesis": "You should tell Bob he is dressed nicely.",
  "label": "Conflict between different principles (Honesty vs. Politeness)",
  "explanation": "There is a prima facie obligation to tell the truth because you should not lie, and there is a prima facie obligation to tell Bob he is dressed nicely because you should be polite. In this case, politeness takes priority because you do not have a trust-based relationship with Bob."
