  "premise": "A murderer asks where your friend is hiding. You know where your friend is. The murderer wants to harm your friend. There is an absolute duty not to lie. You should promote others’ wellbeing.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to tell the truth.",
  "label": "Conflict between different principles (Honesty vs. Beneficence)",
  "explanation": "There is a prima facie obligation to protect your friend and a prima facie obligation not to lie. Because the duty not to lie is absolute, telling the truth takes priority."
},

{
  "id": 4,
  "premise": "A murderer asks where your friend is hiding. You know where your friend is. The murderer wants to harm your friend. You should not lie. You should promote others’ wellbeing.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to lie to protect your friend.",
  "label": "Conflict between different principles (Honesty vs. Beneficence)",
  "explanation": "There is a prima facie obligation not to lie and a prima facie obligation to protect your friend’s life. Protecting your friend’s life takes priority over not lying."
}

{
  "id": 5,
  "premise": "You promised to give money to Bob. Bob lied to manipulate you into making the promise. Mary genuinely needs that money. You should keep your promises. You should promote others’ wellbeing.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to donate the money to Mary.",
  "label": "Conflict between different principles with undercutting condition",
  "explanation": "There is a prima facie obligation to give the money to Bob because you should keep your promises, and a prima facie obligation to help Mary because you should promote others’ wellbeing. But the promise was made under manipulation. So the usual obligation to keep a promise does not apply here."
